-- Italian Stocks Advance; Amplifon, Danieli, Eurotech, Fiat, Popolare Move
-- Francesca Cinelli
-- 2010-07-12T15:45:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-12/banca-popolare-fiat-telecom-italia-may-move-italian-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB  Index
rose for a fifth session, gaining 38.94, or 0.2 percent, to
20,517.92 in Milan.  
 The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  
 Amplifon SpA  (AMP IM) advanced 13.25 cents, or 3.4 percent,
to 4.08 euros, the biggest increase in more than a month.
Mediobanca Securities reiterated an “outperform” rating on the
world’s largest hearing-aid distributor, saying that a potential
acquisition of Australian National Hearing Care Group, active in
Oceania and India, “might anticipate the already known mid-term
targets of the group, with a launch in the Asian markets.”  
 Banca Popolare di Milano Scrl  (PMI IM) dropped from a
three-week high, losing 3.5 cents, or 0.9 percent, to 3.73
euros. EU finance ministers, meeting in Brussels today to
discuss the stress tests on banks, have yet to spell out how
they will deal with a lender that fails the tests and whether
any additional capital will be provided by governments or the
EU.  Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) retreated 6.75 cents, or 1.4
percent, to 4.79 euros.  
 Benetton Group SpA  (BEN IM) gained 9.5 cents, or 1.7
percent, to 5.75 euros, the highest level in more than two
weeks. BofA Merrill Lynch Global Research upgraded Italy’s
biggest clothing retailer to “neutral” from “underperform,”
citing the stock’s recent weakness.  
 Danieli SpA  (DAN IM) lost 36 cents, or 2.4 percent, to
14.57 euros, ending a two-day gain. Goldman Sachs Group Inc.
downgraded Italy’s biggest maker of equipment for the steel
industry to “neutral” from “buy.”  
 ERG Renew SpA  (EGR IM) advanced 2.2 cents, or 2.7 percent,
to 83.7 cents as it signed a memorandum of understanding with
Lukoil to cooperate in the market of renewable energy sources,
focusing on the wind energy segment.  
 Eurotech SpA  (ETH IM) surged 17.75 cents, or 9.6 percent,
to 2.03 euros, the highest level in more than seven weeks. The
Italian company, whose miniature computers are used by Chevron
Corp. and Boeing Co., won a $10 million contract to supply
embedded computers to Cubic Transportation.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM) advanced 18 cents, or 2 percent, to 9
euros, a fifth straight gain. The Italian carmaker that runs
Chrysler Group LLC began talks with banks on a plan to spin off
its industrial operations and to have the units trade
separately, Corriere della Sera reported.  
 Separately, Labor Minister Maurizio Sacconi said the
company’s commitment to produce its Panda model in the
Pomigliano factory near Naples may draw more foreign investors
to the country.  
 STMicroelectronics NV  (STM IM), Europe’s largest chipmaker,
increased 11.5 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 6.63 euros.  
 “Thanks to the effect of the cost-cutting program and
based on a sound financial situation, the current upward cycle
should help STM to restore high levels of operating cash flows,
from H2 2010 onwards and in the following years,” AlphaValue
said in a note.  
